SIMPLE: fodder
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fodder
<hw>Fod"der</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧d"d⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
1st <er>Fother</er>.]</ety> <def>A weight by which lead and some other
metals were formerly sold, in England, varying from 19⟦frac12⟧ to 24
cwt.; a fother.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fodder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fodder
<hw>Fod"der</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧d"d⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>f⟦omac⟧dder</ets>, f⟦omac⟧ddor, fodder (also sheath case), fr.
<ets>f⟦omac⟧da</ets> food; akin to D. <ets>voeder</ets>, OHG.
<ets>fuotar</ets>, G. <ets>futter</ets>, Icel. <ets>f⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧r</ets>,
Sw. & Dan. <ets>foder</ets>. ⟦root⟧75. See <er>Food</er> and cf.
<er>Forage</er>, <er>Fur</er>.]</ety> <def>That which is fed out to
cattle horses, and sheep, as hay, cornstalks, vegetables, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fodder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fodder
<hw>Fod"der</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧d"d⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Foddered</conjf>
<pr>(f⟦ocr⟧d"d⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Foddering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To feed, as cattle, with dry
food or cut grass, etc.; to furnish with hay, straw, oats,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fodderer</ent>⟦br⟧
